 What Where Find Jobs Advanced Job Search Project Instructor Oregon State University 539 reviews Corvallis, OR 97331 Oregon State University 539 reviews Read what people are saying about working here. The School of Electrical Engineering and Computer Science invites applications for a full-time, 12-month, fixed-term Project Instructor position. Reappointment is at the discretion of the School Head. 
 
This position helps students adapt their technical understanding to world-ready skills by preparing and delivering course materials in one or more areas of CS including, but not limited to, the following: Software Engineering, Capstone Design, Introductory Programming, Data Structures, Algorithms, Databases, Artificial Intelligence, Operating Systems, Networking, Security, Web and Cloud Development, and Mobile Development. 
 
Through quality teaching, this role has a pivotal impact on how students perceive the engineering discipline as a whole and how effective they are upon graduation for their future careers. In addition, this position helps student teams by supplying deep practical knowledge of software development. 
 
This position uses various teaching modalities including team co-teaching, remote instruction, in-person instruction, large classrooms/class size, and small group mentoring. 
Position Duties
 90% Teaching: 
 Prepare and teach course materials in one or more areas of CS including, but not limited to, the following: Introductory Programming, Data Structures, Algorithms, Databases, Software Engineering, Operating Systems, Networking, Security, Web and Cloud Development, and Mobile Development. 
 Responsibilities include equipping students with skills required for successful careers, assessing student performance, and/or preparing students to be successful leaders in their chosen profession. 
 May assist in driving curriculum design and development. 
 Responsibilities also include creating an inclusive classroom (e.g., mentoring and supporting students from diverse backgrounds, and fostering affirming classroom interactions across different and challenging structural/cultural barriers that limit movement towards social equity in engineering education and practice). 
 Teaching modalities can vary including team co-teaching, remote instruction, in-person instruction, large classrooms/class size, and small group mentoring. 
 
 5% Supervision: 
 Provide leadership, supervision, and direction for graduate and undergraduate teaching assistants, as well as student workers. 
5% Professional Development: 
 Engage in training, continuing education, and other professional development activities contributing to effectiveness as an instructor. 
Minimum/Required Qualifications
 Master’s Degree in Computer Science, Electrical Engineering or related field. Experience teaching, mentoring, and facilitating learners, inside or outside of a classroom setting. Demonstrated ability to effectively communicate in one or more areas of need in the CS program (specifically: Software Engineering, Introductory Programming, Data Structures, Algorithms, Databases, Artificial Intelligence, Operating Systems, Networking, Security, Web and Cloud Development, and Mobile Development). Demonstrable commitment to promoting and enhancing diversity. Effective written and verbal English skills. 
Preferred (Special) Qualifications
 Proficiency with a breadth of programming tools, frameworks and best practices, including those currently in high demand among employers in the software industry. Experience mentoring early career engineers or student groups in engineering including helping to mentor teams. Supervisory experience, including planning/assigning work, completing performance reviews, and managing team dynamics. 
Working Conditions / Work Schedule
 Working conditions and the work schedule will vary depending on courses assigned 
